How docker actually works, the architecture.

When you typed docker run hello-world, you used the docker command-line client, a small program in your terminal. But that client did not run the container. It sent a request over a unix socket to a long-running daemon, and the daemon did the real work. Understanding this split is what makes troubleshooting later make sense.

Picture four boxes stacked from top to bottom. At the top is the docker command-line interface, the thing you type. It just packages your command as a request and sends it over the socket at slash var slash run slash docker dot sock. Below it is docker daemon, the brain, which manages images, networks, volumes, and container metadata, and listens on that socket by default. Below the daemon is container-d, the runtime supervisor, which tracks the state of containers and handles the low-level image pulling. And at the very bottom is run-see, the small tool that actually creates the namespaces, mounts the root filesystem, sets up control groups, and starts your container's process.

So there are four moving parts. The client, which is stateless and just talks. The daemon, which owns all the state. Container-d, the supervisor, which was donated by docker to the cloud native computing foundation and is used by kubernetes too. And run-see, the tiny open container initiative runtime that does the final act of starting the process, also a cloud native computing foundation project.

Why does any of this matter to you. Two reasons. First, when something breaks, you need to know which layer to look at. The daemon is not running points at docker daemon. A container is wedged might be container-d or run-see. Notebook ten walks through that flow. Second, because the client and daemon are separate, you can point your local docker command at a remote daemon, for example on a beefier server, by setting the docker host environment variable. That is exactly how continuous-integration systems run builds on bigger machines.
